0","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1625":"1625",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England"},"en":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1505–1593":"1505–1593","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1625":"1625",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stobaugh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Staubach  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Staubach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Otto.","German: possibly a Swiss German topographic name from Middle High German <i>stouwen</i> ‘to dam’ + <i>bach</i> ‘creek’ or from Bavarian <i>Staub</i> dust' for a ‘waterfall or stream that seems to turn to dust when falling from a high crag’."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Francis Stobaugh was born in 1505, in Lympne, Kent, England. He married Martha Maddox in 1530, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1550, in Kent, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1505–1593":"1505–1593","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1625":"1625",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1505–1593":"1505–1593","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1625":"1625",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1505–1550":"1505–1550","1505–1593":"1505–1593","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1625":"1625",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Angleterre","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe dist